## 🧠 Engineering & Troubleshooting Notes (Real-World Fixes)

A critical aspect of systems engineering is managing network conflicts. During the initial initialization of this lab, I encountered a major network configuration hurdle:

> ### 🛑 Incident: IP Address Collision / Conflict
> * **Symptom:** Both the Kali Linux analysis workstation and the target server were interacting on the network using overlapping configurations, or reporting conflicting identities on the `192.168.100.249` address space.
> * **The Root Cause Analysis:** When two network interfaces share identical logical identifiers within the same broadcast domain, Address Resolution Protocol (ARP) tables become corrupted. Packets are delivered misrouted, dropping active sessions.
> * **Defensive Resolution Plan:** >   1. Boot each virtual machine independently to avoid live packet drop loops.
>   2. Access the Linux terminal and utilize system utility commands like `ifconfig` or `ip a` to audit interface states.
>   3. Manually adjust configurations to ensure every host maintains a distinct, static IP mapping.

